# Carrier Strike Group

A **carrier strike group** (CSG) is an operational formation of the [United States Navy](/United_States_Navy) and several allied navies. It is centered around an [aircraft carrier](/Aircraft_carrier), which serves as the flagship of the group, and is composed of roughly 7,500 personnel, an [aircraft carrier](/Aircraft_carrier), at least one [cruiser](/Cruiser), a [destroyer squadron](/Destroyer_squadron) of at least two [destroyers](/Destroyer) or [frigates](/Frigate), and a [carrier air wing](/Carrier_air_wing) of 65 to 70 aircraft. The carrier strike group is a flexible naval force that can operate in a variety of roles, including power projection, sea control, and deterrence.

## Composition

The composition of a carrier strike group can vary depending on the mission and the assets available. However, a typical carrier strike group includes the following elements:

### Aircraft Carrier
The centerpiece of the carrier strike group is the [aircraft carrier](/Aircraft_carrier). The United States Navy currently operates [Nimitz-class](/Nimitz-class_aircraft_carrier) and [Gerald R. Ford-class](/Gerald_R._Ford-class_aircraft_carrier) aircraft carriers. These carriers are capable of carrying and launching a variety of aircraft, including [fighter jets](/Fighter_aircraft), [attack aircraft](/Attack_aircraft), [electronic warfare aircraft](/Electronic_warfare_aircraft), and [helicopters](/Helicopter).

### Cruiser
At least one [cruiser](/Cruiser) is typically included in a carrier strike group. The United States Navy uses [Ticonderoga-class](/Ticonderoga-class_cruiser) cruisers, which are equipped with the [Aegis Combat System](/Aegis_Combat_System) and are capable of conducting [anti-air warfare](/Anti-air_warfare), [anti-submarine warfare](/Anti-submarine_warfare), and [anti-surface warfare](/Anti-surface_warfare).

### Destroyer Squadron
A [destroyer squadron](/Destroyer_squadron) of at least two [destroyers](/Destroyer) or [frigates](/Frigate) is also part of the carrier strike group. The United States Navy uses [Arleigh Burke-class](/Arleigh_Burke-class_destroyer) destroyers, which are also equipped with the Aegis Combat System and are capable of conducting a variety of warfare missions.

### Carrier Air Wing
The [carrier air wing](/Carrier_air_wing) is the aviation component of the carrier strike group. It typically consists of 65 to 70 aircraft, including [F/A-18 Hornets](/F/A-18_Hornet), [EA-18G Growlers](/EA-18G_Growler), [E-2 Hawkeyes](/E-2_Hawkeye), and [MH-60R/S Seahawks](/MH-60R/S_Seahawk). The carrier air wing provides the strike group with the ability to conduct [air superiority](/Air_superiority), [strike warfare](/Strike_warfare), [electronic warfare](/Electronic_warfare), and [anti-submarine warfare](/Anti-submarine_warfare) missions.

## Operations

Carrier strike groups are designed to be flexible and can operate in a variety of roles. Some of the primary missions of a carrier strike group include:

### Power Projection
One of the primary roles of a carrier strike group is power projection. The ability to project power from the sea allows the United States to influence events ashore without the need for a large ground presence. This can include conducting [airstrikes](/Airstrike), providing [close air support](/Close_air_support) to ground forces, and conducting [intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance (ISR)](/Intelligence,_surveillance,_target_acquisition,_and_reconnaissance) missions.

### Sea Control
Carrier strike groups are also used for sea control missions. This involves ensuring the freedom of navigation and the ability to use the sea for military and commercial purposes. Sea control missions can include [anti-submarine warfare](/Anti-submarine_warfare), [anti-surface warfare](/Anti-surface_warfare), and [mine countermeasures](/Mine_countermeasures).

### Deterrence
The presence of a carrier strike group can serve as a deterrent to potential adversaries. The ability to project power and conduct a variety of missions can dissuade adversaries from taking aggressive actions. This can include conducting [show of force](/Show_of_force) operations, participating in [military exercises](/Military_exercise), and maintaining a visible presence in key regions.

## History

The concept of the carrier strike group evolved from the [task force](/Task_force) concept used during [World War II](/World_War_II). During the war, the United States Navy organized its carriers into task forces that included a mix of carriers, battleships, cruisers, and destroyers. These task forces were used to conduct a variety of missions, including [air superiority](/Air_superiority), [strike warfare](/Strike_warfare), and [anti-submarine warfare](/Anti-submarine_warfare).

After World War II, the United States Navy continued to refine the concept of the carrier task force. During the [Cold War](/Cold_War), the Navy developed the concept of the carrier battle group, which was centered around a single aircraft carrier and included a mix of cruisers, destroyers, and frigates. The carrier battle group was designed to operate in a variety of roles, including power projection, sea control, and deterrence.

In the post-Cold War era, the United States Navy has continued to evolve the concept of the carrier strike group. The introduction of new technologies, such as the [Aegis Combat System](/Aegis_Combat_System) and the [F-35 Lightning II](/F-35_Lightning_II), has allowed the Navy to enhance the capabilities of its carrier strike groups. Additionally, the Navy has placed a greater emphasis on the ability to operate in [littoral environments](/Littoral_zone), which are the areas close to shore.

## Allied Navies

Several allied navies also operate carrier strike groups. The [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) of the United Kingdom operates the [Queen Elizabeth-class](/Queen_Elizabeth-class_aircraft_carrier) aircraft carriers, which are capable of carrying and launching a variety of aircraft, including the [F-35 Lightning II](/F-35_Lightning_II). The [French Navy](/French_Navy) operates the [Charles de Gaulle](/Charles_de_Gaulle-class_aircraft_carrier), which is a nuclear-powered aircraft carrier capable of carrying and launching a variety of aircraft, including the [Rafale](/Dassault_Rafale).

## Conclusion

The carrier strike group is a flexible and powerful naval formation that is capable of conducting a variety of missions. It is centered around an aircraft carrier and includes a mix of cruisers, destroyers, and frigates, as well as a carrier air wing. The carrier strike group is used for power projection, sea control, and deterrence, and has evolved over time to meet the changing needs of the United States Navy and its allies.

